[
    {
        "content": "<p>Instead of the pipe here...</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>&quot;Default color&quot; |&gt; ANSI.color({ fg: Default, bg: Default })\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>will we be able to dispatch on a <code>Str</code>?</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>&quot;Default color&quot;.color({ fg: Default, bg: Default })\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 495603329,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1737674727
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thinking about this more... it's not a sensible question. <code>Str</code> isn't going to be a Custom Type.</p>",
        "id": 495603551,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1737674864
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm just looking at my ANSI examples... and debating if I refactor these to remove the <code>|&gt;</code></p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code>ANSI.color(&quot;Default color&quot;, { fg: Default, bg: Default })\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 495603705,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1737674976
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thinking about this more... I would probably refactor the API to have a <code>ANSI.styled : Str -&gt; ANSI</code> or similar and then have methods hanging off that to style the string segment. Sounds like a job for future Luke. <span aria-label=\"smiley\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f603\" role=\"img\" title=\"smiley\">:smiley:</span></p>",
        "id": 495603959,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1737675104
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think Str will be a custom type</p>",
        "id": 495605036,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Mohr",
        "timestamp": 1737675740
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And that you can call methods on a string</p>",
        "id": 495605042,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Mohr",
        "timestamp": 1737675750
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the same way List would work</p>",
        "id": 495605068,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Mohr",
        "timestamp": 1737675773
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We <em>need</em> methods like <a href=\"http://List.map\">List.map</a> to work</p>",
        "id": 495605121,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Mohr",
        "timestamp": 1737675814
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Wait so <code>\"str\".color(...)</code> might work? I won't be able to write my own methods because <code>Str</code> is a builtin.</p>",
        "id": 495605142,
        "sender_full_name": "Luke Boswell",
        "timestamp": 1737675838
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That would be my expectation yes</p>",
        "id": 495605261,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Mohr",
        "timestamp": 1737675901
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>no, that would not work</p>",
        "id": 495605272,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1737675908
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In general, methods only get defined in the module of the custom type</p>",
        "id": 495605290,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Mohr",
        "timestamp": 1737675923
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>right</p>",
        "id": 495605297,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1737675929
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>because literally what the <code>.</code> is doing there is saying \"go look up the type of the thing before the <code>.</code> and call a function by this name in its module\"</p>",
        "id": 495605324,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1737675948
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If we didn't require that, then we'd have to do some expensive Rust style trait resolution</p>",
        "id": 495605332,
        "sender_full_name": "Sam Mohr",
        "timestamp": 1737675952
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>so <code>\"str\".color(...)</code> does exactly the same thing as <code>Str.color(\"str\", ...)</code></p>",
        "id": 495605390,
        "sender_full_name": "Richard Feldman",
        "timestamp": 1737675972
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That said, assuming we support <code>.(fn)</code> you would be able to do:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Ruby\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"n\">from</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"no\">ANSI</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">color</span>\n\n<span class=\"s2\">\"Default color\"</span><span class=\"o\">.</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">color</span><span class=\"p\">)({</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ss\">fg</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"no\">Default</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"ss\">bg</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"no\">Default</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">})</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 495621435,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1737686053
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is part of the reason I really want to support <code>.(fn)(...)</code></p>",
        "id": 495621547,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1737686145
    },
